      "writtenOn": "2017-09-12T23:12:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "the explanation (from components/crx_file/id_util.cc in chrome):\n\n// Converts a normal hexadecimal string into the alphabet used by extensions.\n// We use the characters \u0027a\u0027-\u0027p\u0027 instead of \u00270\u0027-\u0027f\u0027 to avoid ever having a\n// completely numeric host, since some software interprets that as an IP\n// address.\n\ni don\u0027t know why a numeric id would matter, since i think these are always referenced via a custom chrome-extension:// scheme, but maybe that wasn\u0027t always the case. https://crrev.com/126074 is where this came from.\n\nthe one thing that i *really* want to know is where the term \"mp-decimal\" to describe this format comes from (catapult/telemetry uses it too, in telemetry/internal/backends/chrome/crx_id.py: \"Convert bytes to an MPDecimal string\"). i\u0027ve poked around http://www.bytereef.org/mpdecimal/ and can\u0027t find any reference to this.",
      "parentUuid": "cdd28691_68c67a04",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 71,
        "startChar": 15,
        "endLine": 71,
        "endChar": 22
      },
      "revId": "a5087cbef1f65990bd9f136f84e0c5b81af180a3",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
